Theoretical prediction shows that low-dimensional materials such as superlattice thin films and nanowires can significantly enhance thermoelectric performance.7,9 Quantum confinement offers one special way to manipulate carrier transports because of the close relationship between electronic band structure and dimensionality. For the thermoelectric materials with quantum dots, the band offset and/or strain field between quantum dots and matrix could act as a confining potential. Therefore, the electronic density of states (dN/dE) has the shape of a Dirac delta function874dN∕dE∝∑ɛiδ(E-ɛi)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
